Notes about revival of Ulm's Oberon System on modern Linux
====================================================================

These notes document all changes we made to build and run ulm's oberon on a modern GNU/Linux operating system. We have used Gentoo on x86_64 (binutils 2.44, elfutils 0.194, kernel 6.12).
We were able to do this because we had preserved the old 0.8.6 binaries built in 2006. We needed those 0.8.6 binaries served as the means to build our newer version. We didn't need the compiler itself but name server and database binaries. Otherwise we could not produce the binaries required for assembling the compiler from existing tof files.


Background
----------
The ULM Oberon system produces 32-bit i386 statically linked ELF executables.
All binaries are statically linked and require no 32-bit userspace libraries;
the kernel's 32-bit (IA-32) execution support is sufficient.

The build system is database-driven:
  pons   - persistent name server (TCP, port 9880/9881)
  cdbd   - compiler database daemon (TCP, port 9882)
  obload - loads compiled module objects from the database
  obtofgen - generates .tof (Transportable Object Format) from .obj
  tof2elf - converts .tof text files to ELF .o relocatable objects

Bootstrap does NOT require running the Oberon compiler: build/tofs.tgz
contains 295 pre-compiled .tof files that are converted directly to .o
and archived into libo.a, then linked with the bootstrap binaries.


Files added
-----------
src/util/oblink/oberon-i386.ld  (NEW)
  Custom GNU ld linker script for all Oberon binaries.
  Required to reproduce the exact single-segment layout that the Oberon
  runtime expects (see "Why a custom linker script" below).


Files modified
--------------
Makefile (top-level)
  - stage1 and stage2 targets used bare `time` command.
    However /usr/bin/time is not installed on our Gentoo system;
    `time` only exists as a bash built-in.
    So we've fixed this by wrapping the command in $(SHELL) -c '...':
        $(SHELL) -c 'time $(BinDir)/mk_obstage ...'

src/util/tof2elf/Makefile
  - Removed -static from LDFLAGS: there is no static libelf.a on many systems.
    tof2elf is a standalone utility; a dynamically linked binary is fine.
  - Added `chmod 755 $@` to the install target (file was copied without
