Why a custom linker script
--------------------------
Two separate problems with modern GNU ld (2.44) required a custom script.

Problem 0: Multiple LOAD segments
  Modern ld produces 4 LOAD segments by default: R (text), RWE, R (rodata),
  RW (data/bss).  The Oberon runtime patches init trampolines at startup,
  which requires all sections to be in a single writable+executable segment.
  With multiple segments, the R segment causes SIGSEGV_ACCERR when the
  runtime tries to patch it.

  The -N flag (used in older binutils) forces a single RWE segment, but
  sets p_align=0x20, which triggers next problem (:.

Problem 1: ASLR and non-page-aligned segments
  With p_align < 0x1000 (PAGE_SIZE), the Linux kernel randomizes the
  brk() starting position even for ET_EXEC (non-PIE) 32-bit binaries
  when ASLR is enabled (randomize_va_space=2).  The MEMINIT startup
  assembly (in genobrts.pl) assumes brk(0) returns an address just past
  the BSS, which is true only when the segment is page-aligned.  With a
  randomized brk, the segment registration arithmetic produces wrong
  addresses and the Memory module's ReserveRegion() raises:
    "assertion failed: given address interval overlaps existing regions"

  Here's why we need our custom `oberon-i386.ld`.
  The linker script creates a single LOAD segment, includes the ELF
  headers (FILEHDR PHDRS) in the segment so the load address matches
  the old 0.8.6 layout, and sets p_align=0x1000 (page size):
```
    OUTPUT_FORMAT("elf32-i386", "elf32-i386", "elf32-i386")
    OUTPUT_ARCH(i386)
    ENTRY(_entry)

    PHDRS
    {
      oberon PT_LOAD FILEHDR PHDRS FLAGS(7);
    }

    SECTIONS
    {
      . = 0x08048000 + SIZEOF_HEADERS;
      .init   : { *(.init)   } :oberon
      .text   : { *(.text)   }
      .rodata : { *(.rodata) }
      .private : { *(.private) *(.data) *(.got) *(.got.plt) }
      .bss    : { *(.bss) *(COMMON) }
      /DISCARD/ : { *(.note*) *(.comment) *(.eh_frame*) }
    }
```
  Result: LOAD 0x000000 0x08048000 0x08048000 0xXXXXXX 0xXXXXXX RWE 0x1000
  This exactly matches the segment layout produced by the old toolchain.


tof2elf fix (modern libelf / elfutils)
---------------------------------------
tof2elf.c is a standalone C program that reads .tof (text) files and
writes 32-bit i386 ELF .o relocatable objects.  It uses Elf32_* types
throughout and explicitly sets e_machine=EM_386, so it produces correct
32-bit output regardless of whether the tof2elf binary itself is 32-bit
or 64-bit.  The host binary can be (and now is) a native 64-bit binary.

Problem was that the old libelf respected user-set Elf_Data.d_off values
when computing the file layout.
The original code used this by creating one Elf_Data chunk per
string/symbol/relocation, manually tracking cumulative offsets
in a counter, setting d_off to that value, and returning it for use as
sh_name or symbol index.

Modern elfutils ignores user-set d_off and recomputes all section offsets
during elf_update().  The sh_name values (set from the manually-tracked
counter) no longer matched where libelf actually placed the strings,
producing sh_name offsets beyond the end of the string table.  `ar` and
`readelf` would report "ELF section name out of range".

Fixed by replacing the one-Elf_Data-per-item pattern with a single growable
buffer per section (string table, symbol table, per-section reloc table).
The buffer is updated in place before elf_update() is called, so libelf
sees a single Elf_Data containing the complete section content.  The
manually-tracked offset counter still correctly reflects the buffer
position and can safely be used as sh_name / symbol index.

The fixed tof2elf.c compiles and works correctly on both 32-bit and 64-bit
Linux systems with modern libelf (elfutils >= 0.150 or so).


Build procedure
--------------------------------------
# Prerequisites: pons and cdbd from the bootstrap installation must be
# running and library sources loaded.

cd /path/to/ulm-oberon-i386-0.8.10

# Start the name server and compiler database daemon:
export ONS_ROOT=127.0.0.1:9880
/home/noch/oberon/bin/start_pons
/home/noch/oberon/bin/start_cdbd
/home/noch/oberon/bin/load_libsources

# Build (and install to DestDir):
make DestDir=/home/noch/oberon

# Bootstrap verification (compile with new binaries, then again with
# stage1 to confirm steady state):
make DestDir=/home/noch/oberon stage1
make DestDir=/home/noch/oberon runstage1
make DestDir=/home/noch/oberon stage2
make DestDir=/home/noch/oberon stage12cmp   # must show no differences

# Install:
make DestDir=/home/noch/oberon install

